Data model (Course) Fields to track:
id: Long (unique identifier)
name: String (course name)
description: String (course description)
targetDate: LocalDate (target completion date; ISO date format)
status: String (Not Started, In Progress, Completed)
Example JSON (courses.json) format: [ { "id": 1, "name": "Intro to Java", "description": "Beginner Java course", "targetDate": "2026-05-01", "status": "Not Started" } ]

REST API endpoints to create
GET /courses
Description: Return all courses
GET /courses/{id}
Description: Return a course by id
POST /courses
Description: Create a new course (supply name, description, targetDate, status)
Request body: JSON Course (id can be omitted; server assigns id)
PUT /courses/{id}
Description: Update an existing course by id
Request body: JSON Course
DELETE /courses/{id}
Description: Delete a course by id
Optional filtering (simple)
GET /courses?status=In%20Progress
GET /courses?name=Java
How to store and retrieve data from JSON file (concept)
Store: Maintain a single JSON array in data/courses.json.
Retrieve: Read and deserialize the array into a List<Course> using Jackson (built into Spring Boot).
Write: Serialize the List<Course> back to data/courses.json.
Concurrency: Basic approach is to synchronize file access to avoid concurrent write issues.
ID generation: Compute the next id by taking max existing id and adding 1.
